               <p>1964. <persName id="def1-1964-18470816" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1964-18470816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1964-18470816" type="surname" value="EASTWICK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1964-18470816" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">JOHN EASTWICK</hi>
                  </persName> was indicted for<rs id="t18470816-1964-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1964-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1964-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> stealing 1 peck of oats, value 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.; the goods of <persName id="t18470816-name-1269" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1269" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1269" type="surname" value="GUIVER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1269" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18470816-1964-offence-1 t18470816-name-1269"></join>Thomas Guiver</persName>, his master; and </rs>
                  <persName id="def2-1964-18470816" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1964-18470816" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1964-18470816" type="surname" value="SHEARMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1964-18470816" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">WILLIAM SHEARMAN</hi>
                  </persName>
                  <rs id="t18470816-1964-offence-2" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1964-offence-2" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18470816-1964-offence-2" type="offenceSubcategory" value="receiving"></interp>, for feloniously receiving the same, knowing them to be stolen.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1271" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1271" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1271" type="surname" value="GUIVER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1271" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>THOMAS GUIVER.</persName>
                  </hi> I am a coach-proprietor, at Cheshunt. I keep my horses at the Ship-inn, Tottenham—Eastwick was my horse-keeper there—I thought it necessary to put some marked papers amongst my oats—I have some oats here which have the papers amongst them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARNWELL.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Does Eastwick feed his horses at Tottenham? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I bring up the oats, and he cuts his own chaff—he had been about five months in my service.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18470816-name-1272" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1272" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1272" type="surname" value="SINCLAIR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18470816-name-1272" type="given" value="RICHARD"></interp>RICHARD SINCLAIR</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">policeman N</hi> 321.) I saw Mr. Guiver on the 14th of Aug., and I gave him some pieces of paper—on the morning of the 17th of Aug. I saw Shearman about the street—I watched, and saw him stop at the Ship, at Tottenham, about two o'clock in the morning—he remained there till about four o'clock—soon after he left I stooped his cart, and found these oats and this chaff—the papers were in the oats—I went and took Eastwick, on a charge of robbing his matter—he said he had not, he had only given <hi rend="italic">Old Billy</hi> some sweepings—there were five pieces of paper found in the oats—I saw one piece picked out.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. PARNELL.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Is the Ship a regular coaching-house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Only Mr. Guiver's horses feed there—other horses stop there—there is one ostler employed by the publican.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you understand who he meant by <hi rend="italic">Old Billy</hi>? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I know Shearman goes by that name—I have known him some years—he said he was seventy-eight years old—I never heard anything particular against him—I had him in custody once about a macintosh—he was in company with a woman that had it—he was discharged, and examined as a witness.</p>
               <p>(Eastwick received a good character.)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">EASTWICK</hi>—<hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <rs id="t18470816-1964-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
